-schemes, where 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=\mathrm{Spec}\,B$
\end_inset

, and where 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi(\mathfrak{q})=A\cap\mathfrak{q}
\]

\end_inset

for all primes 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota\colon A\to B$
\end_inset

 is an integral extension, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is surjective (this is referred to as the 
\series bold
lying over 
\series default
property for integral extensions).
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is continuous with respect to the Zariski topology, for if 
\begin_inset Formula $U:=\mathrm{D}(a)$
\end_inset

 is an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi^{-1}(U)=\pi^{-1}(\mathrm{D}(a))=\mathrm{D}(\iota(a)):=V.
\]

\end_inset

In other words, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $a\notin A\cap\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $a\notin\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

